I";<p>A norm is a <strong>function that</strong> assigns a real-valued length to
each vector. In order to conform to a reasonable notion of length, a norm
must satisfy the following three conditions. For all vectors $x$ and $y$ and for all
scalars $c$  $\in$ $\mathbb{C}$,</p>

<div style="float: right;"> <img src="/numerical-linear-algebra/images/norm-img.png" height="220" width="400" /></div>

<h3 id="conditions">Conditions</h3>
<ol>
  <li>
    <p>$\Vert{x}\Vert \ge 0$ and $\Vert{x}\Vert = 0$ only if $x = 0$</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>$\Vert{x+y}\Vert â‰¤ \Vert{x}\Vert + \Vert{y}\Vert$</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>$\Vert{cx}\Vert = c\Vert{x}\Vert$</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<p><br /></p>
<h3 id="matrix-norms-induced-by-vector-norms">Matrix Norms Induced by Vector Norms</h3>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>Action of A is determined by unit vectors</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Matrix norm is stretch</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<p>\(\Vert{A}\Vert_1\) = Maximum of 1-norm of column vectors of $A$</p>

<p>\(\Vert{A}\Vert_2\) = Largest singular value</p>

<p>$\Vert{A}\Vert_{\infty}$  = Maximum of 1-norm of column vectors of $A^{T}$</p>

<div style="text-align: center;"> <img src="/numerical-linear-algebra/images/mat-norm-img.png" height="300" width="500" /> <figcaption> fig2 - Dashed line mark the vectors most amplified by A </figcaption>
</div>

